1. Score, Age and Gender¶

In this section, we looked at whether the overall work-life balance score differed between the ages and gender of participants. We were interested to see if there would be a between the different age groups. We assumed, that participants between the ages 21 to 50 would have a lower overall score, than people above 50, or below 21, since in this age group, often multiple factors come together that could influence the work-life balance, e.g. new job, young children, and so on. We also wanted to see if there were differences between male and female.

In [ ]:
fig, ax= plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1, figsize=(7,7))
ax = sns.barplot(data=df, x="age", y="score", hue="gender", order=['20 or less', '21 to 35', '36 to 50', '51 or more'],)

ax.set(ylim=(500, 700))
plt.show()

For that we first used a barplot, grouped by age and gender.

In [ ]:
totalScore_age_gender = df.groupby(['age','gender'], as_index=False)['score'].mean()
fig, ax= plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1, figsize=(7,7))
ax = sns.pointplot(x='age', y='score',hue='gender', dodge=True, data=totalScore_age_gender, ci=68, ax=ax,palette=sns.color_palette("rocket_r"))
#ylimit (ylim...)

ax.set(ylabel='total score')

plt.show()

We used the pointplot afterwards, that makes it easier to spot differences between two (or more) groups, in this case male and female.

Observations¶

  • There seems to be a correlation between age and the total work-life balance score, with higher ages, the overall work-life balance score tends to be higher
  • the score seems to also be higher in the '20 or less' group, but here it is still smaller than in the '36 to 50' group, not quite matching our hypothesis
  • however the difference between the total scores is relatively small (as can be seen in the barplot)
  • the maximum difference is between the group of '21 to 35' and the '51 or more' years old and is around 15 points for both male and female
  • there also seems to be a small difference between male and female
  • males tend to have a smaller total score, except in the group '20 or less'
  • the mean difference in male and female total score is around 4-5 points

2. Income and stress level/time for hobbies¶

In this section we wanted to see, if people with sufficient or hardly suffienct income showed differences in the stress level and time for hobbies. We assumed, that people with sufficient income showed less stress and more time for hobbies than people with hardly sufficient income.

Observations¶

  • the second histplot shows the distribution of "time for passion" that participants reported
  • it seems to be normally distributed, but slightly shifted towards the left, meaning towards less time for passion/hobbies
  • this is also depicted by the mean (~ 3.6) as well as the median (3.5)
  • the third histplot shows the distribution of "daily stress", which again seems to be normally distributed
  • there seems to be a slight shift to the right, with a mean of ~2.8 and a median of 3
  • the distribution in both plots seems to be roughly equal for insufficient, as well as sufficient income
  • the last plot shows the relation between daily stress and time for passion, in relation to the income
  • there seems to be a negative correlation between daily stress and time for passion with higher daily stress correlating with less time for passion, and vice verza
  • participants with less income tend to have higher daily stress, with a difference of around 0.5 points

3. Life Vision¶

In this section, we will visualize how clearly participants of the survey of different age groups and genders could imagine their future (For how many years ahead is your life vision clear for you?). Our hypothesis is, that the older one gets, the clearer the life vision. We also assume, that men are more clear about what they wil be doing in the years ahead as they typically stay in their career path, while women might change their jobs or stop working completely after having children.

In [ ]:
# REPRESENTATION

ax.set(ylabel='Years of Life Vision',xlabel='Age')

The plot clearly supports our suggestion, that men are clear about their life for a longer period of time. For us, although we did hypothesise about this, we are still surprised, that in our emancipated world, it is still the case that women are more unsure how the next years of their lifes will look like than men.

6. The 5 Pillars of a Good Lifestyle¶

The Work-Life Balance survey evaluates how we thrive in both our professional and personal lives: it reflects how well we shape our lifestyle, habits and behaviors to maximize our overall life satisfaction along the following five dimensions:

  1. Healthy body, reflecting fitness and healthy habits;
  2. Healthy mind, indicating how well we embrace positive emotions;
  3. Expertise, measuring the ability to grow expertise and achieve something unique;
  4. Connection, assessing the strength of our social network and inclination to discover the world;
  5. Meaning, evaluating our compassion, generosity and how much we are living the life of our dream.

In the following code blocks, we assigned the questions into the 5 different categories to see how well the subjects do in different pillars of their life and whether there are patterns across age or gender.

In [ ]:
#assign categories to pillars

#scores are the sum of the achieved points divided by the maximum of achievable points
body_score = df[['bmi_range','fruits_veggies','daily_steps','sleep_hours']].sum(axis = 1)/40
mind_score = ((30-df[['lost_vacation','daily_stress','daily_shouting']].sum(axis = 1)) + df[['time_for_passion','weekly_meditation']].sum(axis = 1))/50
expertise_score = df[['personal_awards','achievement','todo_completed','sufficient_income']].sum(axis = 1)/40
connection_score = df[['social_network','core_circle','places_visited']].sum(axis = 1)/30
meaning_score = df[['life_vision','donation','supporting_others','flow']].sum(axis = 1)/40
total_score = body_score + mind_score + expertise_score + connection_score + meaning_score
In [ ]:
#create dict with percentages of pillars
pillars = {'body': (body_score/total_score)*100,
        'mind' : (mind_score/total_score)*100,
        'expertise' : (expertise_score/total_score)*100,
        'connection' : (connection_score/total_score)*100,
        'meaning' : (meaning_score/total_score)*100
        }

# convert into dataframe
pillars_df = pd.DataFrame(pillars)

#add subject gender and age
pillars_df['age']=df['age']
pillars_df['gender']=df['gender']

7. Stress and Wellbeing¶

From daily life struggles we know that Wellbeing and Stress mostly do not contribute. But is this really true? And if yes what does contribute most to Stress? In the Dataset Lifestyle and Wellbeing a lot of different Informations were gathered and we can now check if these Contributions are correct and also if there are any possibilities to reduce our daily stress.

Is it true, that Stress and a Work-Life-Balance have a negative correlation?

In [ ]:
# contribution of Stress and Work-Life-Balance

fig, ax= plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1, figsize=(8,4))


ax = sns.pointplot(data=df, x='daily_stress', y='score',sort = True, color="#B91357")

ax.set(ylabel='Work-Life-Balance Score')
ax.set(xlabel='Daily Stress')

plt.show()

Observation:

Wellbeing and Daily Stress are correlating, but they have a negative correlation. From the Diagram we cannot tell if Daily Stress is affecting the the decrease of the Wellbeing Score, or if it the other way around. We can for sure say, that there is a Contribution between Stress and the Wellbeing Score.

What contributes with the daily stress level, which does affect it positive and which affects the stress negative?

Therefore the Correlation of Daily Shouting, Lost Vacations, Sleeping Hours, Hobbys, Meditation and Daily Stress will be shown. For this purpose the people were asked to rate how many days of vacation they typically lose every year, how often they shout or sulk at somebody and how long the typically sleep.

To answer this Question from both sides, we made two plots in the left Graph we will observe the how the Increase of Sleep, Time for Passion and weekly Meditatin affects on the Daily Stress. In the right Graph we will observe how the Increase of Daily Stress has an affect on Time for Sleep, Passion and Meditation. Therefore we switched the x- and y-axis of the Graphs.

On the left Graph, we can see that the range between people having about 1 hour of sleep per night and having a lot of stress and not a lot of stress differs widely. Also the with the Increase of Sleep, Meditation and Time for Passion/Hobbies the Stress Level decreases. Whereas on the right Graph it looks as the increase of Daily Stress contradicts the decrease of especially Meditation and Time for Passion and the Amount of Sleeps remains nearly the same. Still we cannot say which contradicts each other more, but we can tell that there is a Correlation between the Time for Mediation and Passion and the Daily Stress Level.

8. General Correlations¶

Since we are coming to an end of this notebook, let's have a last look at all the Contributions between all the attributes from the dataset. Therefore we will use a Heatmap where we can see if there is a positive correlation (red) or a negative correlation (blue), or no found correlation (white) between the attributes.

sns.set_theme(style="white")


corr = df.corr()

mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))

# Set up the matplotlib figure
f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))

# Generate a custom diverging colormap
cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)

# Draw the heatmap with the mask and correct aspect ratio
sns.heatmap(corr, mask=mask, cmap=cmap, vmax=.5, center=0,
            square=True, linewidths=.2, cbar_kws={"shrink": .5}, linecolor='white')
